definition.value: A methyl-branched fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 3-methyl fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A methyl-branched fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 2-methyl fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-glutamic acid at the amino group or either of the carboxy groups, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-glutamic acid by a heteroatom.
Any phospho sugar that is the phosphate derivative of pentose.
Any metabolite (endogenous or exogenous) found in human urine samples.
Carbohydrate derivatives resulting from the non-enzymatic glycosylation of proteins. They result in cells becoming stiffer and more prone to damage and premature aging.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-serine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-serine by a heteroatom.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of pentacosanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid obtained by protonation of the amino group of any 2-amino-1,3-dihydroxysphingoid base.
A cationic sphingoid obtained by protonation of the amino group of any 3-dehydrosphingoid base. Major species at pH 7.3.
A  1-(Z)-alk-1-enyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alk-1-enyl and acyl groups are specified as (1Z)-octadecenyl and linoleoyl (9Z,12Z-octadecadienoyl) respectively.
Any member of the class of  indoles carrying at least one hydroxy group.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in algae including unicellular organisms like chlorella and diatoms to multicellular organisms like giant kelps and brown algae.
A phosphatidylcholine 38:6 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are specified as palmitoyl and (4E,7E,10E,13E,16E,19E)-docosahexaenoyl respectively.
A carbocyclic fatty acid composed of heptanoic acid having a (1S,2S)-2-octylcyclopentyl substituent at position 7.
Any cosmetic used to lighten the colour of skin by reducing the concentration of melanin.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is a deacylated sphingomyelin with undefined sphingoid base.
Any metabolite (endogenous or exogenous) found in human blood serum samples.
Any substance that inhibits the action of glycine transporters.
A diglyceride in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 32 carbons and 0 double bond.
A ceramide in which the acyl group and the sphingoid base contain a total of 42 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A ceramide in which the acyl group and the sphingoid base contain a total of 42 carbon atoms and 2 double bonds.

A 1-O-(alk-1-enyl)-2-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the unspecified alk-1-enyl and acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain 36 carbon atoms in total with 2 additional double bonds in the acyl moiety.
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in rat (Rattus norvegicus).
A tyrosine derivative that is tyrosine substituted by a nitro group at unspecified position. A "closed" class.
Any antifungal agent used to prevent or treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
A gluconic acid having L-configuration.
Any O-acylcarnitine in which the acyl group contains a total of 9 carbon atoms.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the  conjugate base of alpha-aminobutyric acid.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of two of the three diphosphate OH groups of adenosine 5'-diphosphate.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the  six amino groups of framycetin; major species at pH 7.3.

An anionic ganglioside obtained by deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy groups of any member of the GM1/1b family of gangliosides; major species at pH 7.3. GM1/1b ganglioside head groups include 4 neutral sugar groups and 1 sialic acid group.
Any organic amino compound that contains two or more amino groups.
Any metal which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
Any drug which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
An organic anion obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group of 2-hydroxy-5-methylquinone. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An EC 6.4.1.* (carboxylase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1).
A lysophosphatidylethanolamine in which the acyl group has a fully saturated C16 chain and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hexadecatrienoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A drug that acts as an antagonist, agonist, reverse agonist, or in some other fashion when interacting with cellular receptors.
Any peptide zwitterion comprising two amino acid residues. Major structure at pH 7.3.
A carboxylic acic anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any aromatic carboxylic acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 40 carbons in total with 7 double bonds.

An organic heterotricyclic compound that is a hexa-oxygenated 6,7-guaianolide isolated fron the roots of Thapsia garganica L., Apiaceae. A potent skin irritant, it is used in traditional medicine as a counter-irritant. Thapsigargin inhibits Ca(2+)-transporting ATPase mediated uptake of calcium ions into sarcoplasmic reticulum and is used in experimentation examining the impacts of increasing cytosolic calcium concentrations.

A family of cyclic nonapeptide hormones found in most mammals. Synthesised in the hypothalamus and stored in the post-pituitary, vasopressins play a key role in homeostasis, particularly in regulating the body's water content. Together with the similar neuropeptide oxytocin, they are believed to influence social cognition and behaviour.
